# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloth-simulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] Most models of cloth are based on "particles" of mass connected in some manner of mesh.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] Newtonian physics is used to model each particle through the use of a "black box" called a physics engine.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] In all of these models, the goal is to find the position and shape of a piece of fabric using this basic equation and several other methods.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] Jerry Weil pioneered the first of these, the geometric technique, in 1986.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] His work was focused on approximating the look of cloth by treating cloth like a collection of cables and using hyperbolic cosine (catenary) curves.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] Because of this, it is not suitable for dynamic models but works very well for stationary or single-frame renders.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] This technique creates an underlying shape out of single points; then, it parses through each set of three of these points and maps a catenary curve to the set.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] It then takes the lowest out of each overlapping set and uses it for the render.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] The second technique treats cloth like a grid work of particles connected to each other by springs.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] Now we apply the basic principle of mechanical equilibrium in which all bodies seek lowest energy by differentiating this equation to find the minimum energy.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] The last method is more complex than the first two.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] The particle technique takes the physical methods a step further and supposes that we have a network of particles interacting directly.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] Rather than springs, the energy interactions of the particles are used to determine the cloth's shape.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] Terms for energy added by any source can be added to this equation, then derive and find minima, which generalizes our model.
[src:cloth-simulation/cloth-modeling] This allows for modeling cloth behavior under any circumstance, and since the cloth is treated as a collection of particles its behavior can be described with the dynamics provided in our physics engine.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FEM is a general numerical method for solving partial differential equations in two- or three-space variables (i.e., some boundary value problems).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] There are also studies about using FEM to solve high-dimensional problems.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] To solve a problem, FEM subdivides a large system into smaller, simpler parts called **finite elements**.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This is achieved by a particular space discretization in the space dimensions, which is implemented by the construction of a mesh of the object: the numerical domain for the solution that has a finite number of points.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FEM formulation of a boundary value problem finally results in a system of algebraic equations.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The method approximates the unknown function over the domain.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The simple equations that model these finite elements are then assembled into a larger system of equations that models the entire problem.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FEM then approximates a solution by minimizing an associated error function via the calculus of variations.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Studying or analyzing a phenomenon with FEM is often referred to as **finite element analysis** (FEA).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] by the coil (rectangular area on the right).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] , as indicated by the scale in the inset legend, red being high amplitude.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The area inside the cylinder is low amplitude (dark blue, with widely spaced lines of magnetic flux), which suggests that the shield is performing as it was designed to.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Systematically recombining all sets of element equations into a global system of equations for the final calculation.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The global system of equations uses known solution techniques and can be calculated from the initial values of the original problem to obtain a numerical answer.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In the first step above, the element equations are simple equations that locally approximate the original complex equations to be studied, where the original equations are often partial differential equations (PDEs).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] To explain the approximation of this process, FEM is commonly introduced as a special case of the Galerkin method.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The process, in mathematical language, is to construct an integral of the inner product of the residual and the weight functions; then, set the integral to zero.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In simple terms, it is a procedure that minimizes the approximation error by fitting trial functions into the PDE.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The residual is the error caused by the trial functions, and the weight functions are polynomial approximation functions that project the residual.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] These equation sets are element equations.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] They are linear if the underlying PDE is linear and vice versa.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Algebraic equation sets that arise in the steady-state problems are solved using numerical linear algebraic methods.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In contrast, ordinary differential equation sets that occur in the transient problems are solved by numerical integrations using standard techniques such as Euler's method or the Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In the second step above, a global system of equations is generated from the element equations by transforming coordinates from the subdomains' local nodes to the domain's global nodes.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This spatial transformation includes appropriate orientation adjustments as applied in relation to the reference coordinate system.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The process is often carried out using FEM software with coordinate data generated from the subdomains.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The practical application of FEM is known as finite element analysis (FEA).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FEA, as applied in engineering, is a computational tool for performing engineering analysis.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It includes the use of mesh generation techniques for dividing a complex problem into smaller elements, as well as the use of software coded with a FEM algorithm.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FEA may be used for analyzing problems over complicated domains (e.g., cars and oil pipelines) when the domain changes (e.g., during a solid-state reaction with a moving boundary), when the desired precision varies over the entire domain, or when the solution lacks smoothness.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FEA simulations provide a valuable resource, as they remove multiple instances of creating and testing complex prototypes for various high-fidelity situations.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For example, in a frontal crash simulation, it is possible to increase prediction accuracy in important areas, like the front of the car, and reduce it in the rear of the car, thus reducing the cost of the simulation.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Another example would be in numerical weather prediction, where it is more important to have accurate predictions over developing highly nonlinear phenomena, such as tropical cyclones in the atmosphere or eddies in the ocean, rather than relatively calm areas.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] A clear, detailed, and practical presentation of this approach can be found in the textbook *The Finite Element Method for Engineers*.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] While it is difficult to quote the date of the invention of FEM, the method originated from the need to solve complex elasticity and structural analysis problems in civil and aeronautical engineering.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Its development can be traced back to work by Alexander Hrennikoff and Richard Courant in the early 1940s.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In the USSR, the introduction of the practical application of FEM is usually connected with Leonard Oganesyan.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It was also independently rediscovered in China by Feng Kang in the late 1950s and early 1960s, based on the computations of dam constructions, where it was called the "finite difference method" based on variation principles.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Although the approaches used by these pioneers are different, they share one essential characteristic: the mesh discretization of a continuous domain into a set of discrete sub-domains, usually called elements.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Hrennikoff's work discretizes the domain by using a lattice analogy, while Courant's approach divides the domain into finite triangular sub-regions to solve second-order elliptic partial differential equations that arise from the problem of the torsion of a cylinder.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Courant's contribution was evolutionary, drawing on a large body of earlier results for PDEs developed by Lord Rayleigh, Walther Ritz, and Boris Galerkin.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The application of FEM gained momentum in the 1960s and 1970s due to the developments of J.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Argyris and his co-workers at the University of Stuttgart; R.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Clough and his co-workers at University of California Berkeley; O.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Zienkiewicz and his co-workers Ernest Hinton, Bruce Irons, and others at Swansea University; Philippe G.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Ciarlet at the University of Paris 6; and Richard Gallagher and his co-workers at Cornell University.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] During this period, additional impetus was provided by the available open-source FEM programs.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] NASA sponsored the original version of NASTRAN.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] University of California Berkeley made the finite element programs SAP IV and, later, OpenSees widely available.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In Norway, the ship classification society Det Norske Veritas (now DNV GL) developed Sesam in 1969 for use in the analysis of ships.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] A rigorous mathematical basis for FEM was provided in 1973 with a publication by Gilbert Strang and George Fix.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The method has since been generalized for the numerical modeling of physical systems in a wide variety of engineering disciplines, such as electromagnetism, heat transfer, and fluid dynamics.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] A finite element method is characterized by a variational formulation, a discretization strategy, one or more solution algorithms, and post-processing procedures.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Examples of the variational formulation are the Galerkin method, the discontinuous Galerkin method, mixed methods, etc.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] A discretization strategy is understood to mean a clearly defined set of procedures that cover (a) the creation of finite element meshes, (b) the definition of basis function on reference elements (also called shape functions), and (c) the mapping of reference elements onto the elements of the mesh.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Examples of discretization strategies are the h-version, p-version, hp-version, x-FEM, isogeometric analysis, etc.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Each discretization strategy has certain advantages and disadvantages.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] A reasonable criterion in selecting a discretization strategy is to realize nearly optimal performance for the broadest set of mathematical models in a particular model class.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Various numerical solution algorithms can be classified into two broad categories; direct and iterative solvers.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] These algorithms are designed to exploit the sparsity of matrices that depend on the variational formulation and discretization strategy choices.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Post-processing procedures are designed to extract the data of interest from a finite element solution.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] To meet the requirements of solution verification, postprocessors need to provide for *a posteriori* error estimation in terms of the quantities of interest.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] When the errors of approximation are larger than what is considered acceptable, then the discretization has to be changed either by an automated adaptive process or by the action of the analyst.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Some very efficient postprocessors provide for the realization of superconvergence.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The following two problems demonstrate the finite element method.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] P1 is a one-dimensional problem ${\text{ P1 }}:{\begin{cases}u''(x)=f(x){\text{ in }}(0,1),\\u(0)=u(1)=0,\end{cases}}$ where f is given, u is an unknown function of x , and $u''$ is the second derivative of u with respect to x .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] where $\Omega$ is a connected open region in the $(x,y)$ plane whose boundary $\partial \Omega$ is nice (e.g., a smooth manifold or a polygon), and $u_{xx}$ and $u_{yy}$ denote the second derivatives with respect to x and y , respectively.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The problem P1 can be solved directly by computing antiderivatives.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] However, this method of solving the boundary value problem (BVP) works only when there is one spatial dimension.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It does not generalize to higher-dimensional problems or problems like $u+V''=f$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For this reason, we will develop the finite element method for P1 and outline its generalization to P2.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Our explanation will proceed in two steps, which mirror two essential steps one must take to solve a boundary value problem (BVP) using the FEM.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] After this second step, we have concrete formulae for a large but finite-dimensional linear problem whose solution will approximately solve the original BVP.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This finite-dimensional problem is then implemented on a computer.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The first step is to convert P1 and P2 into their equivalent weak formulations.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Conversely, if u with $u(0)=u(1)=0$ satisfies (1) for every smooth function $v(x)$ then one may show that this u will solve P1.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The proof is easier for twice continuously differentiable u (mean value theorem) but may be proved in a distributional sense as well.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] where we have used the assumption that $v(0)=v(1)=0$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] where $\nabla$ denotes the gradient and $\cdot$ denotes the dot product in the two-dimensional plane.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Once more $\,\!\phi$ can be turned into an inner product on a suitable space $H_{0}^{1}(\Omega )$ of once differentiable functions of $\Omega$ that are zero on $\partial \Omega$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] We have also assumed that $v\in H_{0}^{1}(\Omega )$ (see Sobolev spaces).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The existence and uniqueness of the solution can also be shown.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] We can loosely think of $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$ to be the absolutely continuous functions of $(0,1)$ that are 0 at $x=0$ and $x=1$ (see Sobolev spaces).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Such functions are (weakly) once differentiable, and it turns out that the symmetric bilinear map $\!\,\phi$ then defines an inner product which turns $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$ into a Hilbert space (a detailed proof is nontrivial).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] On the other hand, the left-hand-side $\int _{0}^{1}f(x)v(x)dx$ is also an inner product, this time on the Lp space $L^{2}(0,1)$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] An application of the Riesz representation theorem for Hilbert spaces shows that there is a unique u solving (2) and, therefore, P1.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This solution is a-priori only a member of $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$ , but using elliptic regularity, will be smooth if f is.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] P1 and P2 are ready to be discretized, which leads to a common sub-problem (3).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] where V is a finite-dimensional subspace of $H_{0}^{1}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] There are many possible choices for V (one possibility leads to the spectral method).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] However, we take V as a space of piecewise polynomial functions for the finite element method.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Observe that functions in V are not differentiable according to the elementary definition of calculus.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Indeed, if $v\in V$ then the derivative is typically not defined at any $x=x_{k}$ , $k=1,\ldots ,n$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] However, the derivative exists at every other value of x , and one can use this derivative for integration by parts.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] We need V to be a set of functions of $\Omega$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] One hopes that as the underlying triangular mesh becomes finer and finer, the solution of the discrete problem (3) will, in some sense, converge to the solution of the original boundary value problem P2.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] To measure this mesh fineness, the triangulation is indexed by a real-valued parameter $h>0$ which one takes to be very small.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This parameter will be related to the largest or average triangle size in the triangulation.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] As we refine the triangulation, the space of piecewise linear functions V must also change with h .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For this reason, one often reads $V_{h}$ instead of V in the literature.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Since we do not perform such an analysis, we will not use this notation.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] To complete the discretization, we must select a basis of V .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] for $k=1,\dots ,n$ ; this basis is a shifted and scaled tent function.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For the two-dimensional case, we choose again one basis function $v_{k}$ per vertex $x_{k}$ of the triangulation of the planar region $\Omega$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The function $v_{k}$ is the unique function of V whose value is 1 at $x_{k}$ and zero at every $x_{j},\;j\neq k$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Depending on the author, the word "element" in the "finite element method" refers to the domain's triangles, the piecewise linear basis function, or both.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] So, for instance, an author interested in curved domains might replace the triangles with curved primitives and so might describe the elements as being curvilinear.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] On the other hand, some authors replace "piecewise linear" with "piecewise quadratic" or even "piecewise polynomial".
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The author might then say "higher order element" instead of "higher degree polynomial".
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The finite element method is not restricted to triangles (tetrahedra in 3-d or higher-order simplexes in multidimensional spaces).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Still, it can be defined on quadrilateral subdomains (hexahedra, prisms, or pyramids in 3-d, and so on).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Higher-order shapes (curvilinear elements) can be defined with polynomial and even non-polynomial shapes (e.g., ellipse or circle).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Examples of methods that use higher degree piecewise polynomial basis functions are the hp-FEM and spectral FEM.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] (The matrix containing $\langle v_{j},v_{k}\rangle$ in the $(j,k)$ location is known as the Gramian matrix.) In the one dimensional case, the support of $v_{k}$ is the interval $[x_{k-1},x_{k+1}]$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Hence, the integrands of $\langle v_{j},v_{k}\rangle$ and $\phi (v_{j},v_{k})$ are identically zero whenever $|j-k|>1$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Similarly, in the planar case, if $x_{j}$ and $x_{k}$ do not share an edge of the triangulation, then the integrals $\int _{\Omega }v_{j}v_{k}\,ds$ and $\int _{\Omega }\nabla v_{j}\cdot \nabla v_{k}\,ds$ are both zero.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] As we have discussed before, most of the entries of L and M are zero because the basis functions $v_{k}$ have small support.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] So we now have to solve a linear system in the unknown $\mathbf {u}$ where most of the entries of the matrix L , which we need to invert, are zero.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Such matrices are known as sparse matrices, and there are efficient solvers for such problems (much more efficient than actually inverting the matrix.) In addition, L is symmetric and positive definite, so a technique such as the conjugate gradient method is favored.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For problems that are not too large, sparse LU decompositions and Cholesky decompositions still work well.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For instance, MATLAB's backslash operator (which uses sparse LU, sparse Cholesky, and other factorization methods) can be sufficient for meshes with a hundred thousand vertices.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The matrix L is usually referred to as the stiffness matrix, while the matrix M is dubbed the mass matrix.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In general, the finite element method is characterized by the following process.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Separate consideration is the smoothness of the basis functions.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For second-order elliptic boundary value problems, piecewise polynomial basis function that is merely continuous suffice (i.e., the derivatives are discontinuous.) For higher-order partial differential equations, one must use smoother basis functions.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For instance, for a fourth-order problem such as $u_{xxxx}+u_{yyyy}=f$ , one may use piecewise quadratic basis functions that are $C^{1}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Another consideration is the relation of the finite-dimensional space V to its infinite-dimensional counterpart in the examples above $H_{0}^{1}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] A conforming element method is one in which space V is a subspace of the element space for the continuous problem.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] If this condition is not satisfied, we obtain a nonconforming element method, an example of which is the space of piecewise linear functions over the mesh, which are continuous at each edge midpoint.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Since these functions are generally discontinuous along the edges, this finite-dimensional space is not a subspace of the original $H_{0}^{1}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Typically, one has an algorithm for subdividing a given mesh.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Under specific hypotheses (for instance, if the domain is convex), a piecewise polynomial of order d method will have an error of order $p=d+1$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] If instead of making *h* smaller, one increases the degree of the polynomials used in the basis function, one has a *p*-method.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] If one combines these two refinement types, one obtains an *hp*-method (hp-FEM).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In the hp-FEM, the polynomial degrees can vary from element to element.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] High-order methods with large uniform *p* are called spectral finite element methods (SFEM).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] These are not to be confused with spectral methods.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For vector partial differential equations, the basis functions may take values in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The Applied Element Method or AEM combines features of both FEM and Discrete element method or (DEM).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Yang and Lui introduced the Augmented-Finite Element Method, whose goal was to model the weak and strong discontinuities without needing extra DoFs, as PuM stated.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The Cut Finite Element Approach was developed in 2014.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The generalized finite element method (GFEM) uses local spaces consisting of functions, not necessarily polynomials, that reflect the available information on the unknown solution and thus ensure good local approximation.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Then a partition of unity is used to "bond" these spaces together to form the approximating subspace.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The effectiveness of GFEM has been shown when applied to problems with domains having complicated boundaries, problems with micro-scales, and problems with boundary layers.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The mixed finite element method is a type of finite element method in which extra independent variables are introduced as nodal variables during the discretization of a partial differential equation problem.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The hp-FEM combines adaptively elements with variable size *h* and polynomial degree *p* to achieve exceptionally fast, exponential convergence rates.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The hpk-FEM combines adaptively elements with variable size *h*, polynomial degree of the local approximations *p*, and global differentiability of the local approximations (*k*-1) to achieve the best convergence rates.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The extended finite element method (XFEM) is a numerical technique based on the generalized finite element method (GFEM) and the partition of unity method (PUM).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It extends the classical finite element method by enriching the solution space for solutions to differential equations with discontinuous functions.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Extended finite element methods enrich the approximation space to naturally reproduce the challenging feature associated with the problem of interest: the discontinuity, singularity, boundary layer, etc.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It was shown that for some problems, such an embedding of the problem's feature into the approximation space can significantly improve convergence rates and accuracy.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] XFEM has also been implemented in codes like Altair Radios, ASTER, Morfeo, and Abaqus.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It is increasingly being adopted by other commercial finite element software, with a few plugins and actual core implementations available (ANSYS, SAMCEF, OOFELIE, etc.).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The introduction of the scaled boundary finite element method (SBFEM) came from Song and Wolf (1997).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The SBFEM has been one of the most profitable contributions in the area of numerical analysis of fracture mechanics problems.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It is a semi-analytical fundamental-solutionless method combining the advantages of finite element formulations and procedures and boundary element discretization.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] However, unlike the boundary element method, no fundamental differential solution is required.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The S-FEM, Smoothed Finite Element Methods, is a particular class of numerical simulation algorithms for the simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It was developed by combining mesh-free methods with the finite element method.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Spectral element methods combine the geometric flexibility of finite elements and the acute accuracy of spectral methods.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Spectral methods are the approximate solution of weak-form partial equations based on high-order Lagrangian interpolants and used only with certain quadrature rules.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Loubignac iteration is an iterative method in finite element methods.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The crystal plasticity finite element method (CPFEM) is an advanced numerical tool developed by Franz Roters.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Metals can be regarded as crystal aggregates, which behave anisotropy under deformation, such as abnormal stress and strain localization.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] CPFEM, based on the slip (shear strain rate), can calculate dislocation, crystal orientation, and other texture information to consider crystal anisotropy during the routine.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] It has been applied in the numerical study of material deformation, surface roughness, fractures, etc.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The virtual element method (VEM), introduced by Beirão da Veiga et al.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] (2013) as an extension of mimetic finite difference (MFD) methods, is a generalization of the standard finite element method for arbitrary element geometries.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This allows admission of general polygons (or polyhedra in 3D) that are highly irregular and non-convex in shape.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The name *virtual* derives from the fact that knowledge of the local shape function basis is not required and is, in fact, never explicitly calculated.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Some types of finite element methods (conforming, nonconforming, mixed finite element methods) are particular cases of the gradient discretization method (GDM).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Hence the convergence properties of the GDM, which are established for a series of problems (linear and nonlinear elliptic problems, linear, nonlinear, and degenerate parabolic problems), hold as well for these particular FEMs.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The finite difference method (FDM) is an alternative way of approximating solutions of PDEs.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Generally, FEM is the method of choice in all types of analysis in structural mechanics (i.e., solving for deformation and stresses in solid bodies or dynamics of structures).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In contrast, computational fluid dynamics (CFD) tend to use FDM or other methods like finite volume method (FVM).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] CFD problems usually require discretization of the problem into a large number of cells/gridpoints (millions and more).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Therefore the cost of the solution favors simpler, lower-order approximation within each cell.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This is especially true for 'external flow' problems, like airflow around the car, airplane, or weather simulation.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Another method used for approximating solutions to a partial differential equation is the Fast Fourier Transform (FFT), where the solution is approximated by a Fourier series computed using the FFT.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] For approximating the mechanical response of materials under stress, FFT is often much faster, but FEM may be more accurate.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] One example of the respective advantages of the two methods is in simulation of rolling a sheet of aluminum (an FCC metal), and drawing a wire of tungsten (a BCC metal).
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This simulation did not have a sophisticated shape update algorithm for the FFT method.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In both cases, the FFT method was more than 10 times as fast as FEM, but in the wire drawing simulation, where there were large deformations in grains, the FEM method was much more accurate.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In the sheet rolling simulation, the results of the two methods were similar.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FFT has a larger speed advantage in cases where the boundary conditions are given in the materials strain, and loses some of its efficiency in cases where the stress is used to apply the boundary conditions, as more iterations of the method are needed.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The FE and FFT methods can also be combined in a voxel based method (2) to simulate deformation in materials, where the FE method is used for the macroscale stress and deformation, and the FFT method is used on the microscale to deal with the effects of microscale on the mechanical response.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Unlike FEM, FFT methods' similarities to image processing methods means that an actual image of the microstructure from a microscope can be input to the solver to get a more accurate stress response.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Using a real image with FFT avoids meshing the microstructure, which would be required if using FEM simulation of the microstructure, and might be difficult.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Because Fourier approximations are inherently periodic, FFT can only be used in cases of periodic microstructure, but this is common in real materials.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FFT can also be combined with FEM methods by using Fourier components as the variational basis for approximating the fields inside an element, which can take advantage of the speed of FFT based solvers.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Various specializations under the umbrella of the mechanical engineering discipline (such as aeronautical, biomechanical, and automotive industries) commonly use integrated FEM in the design and development of their products.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Several modern FEM packages include specific components such as thermal, electromagnetic, fluid, and structural working environments.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In a structural simulation, FEM helps tremendously in producing stiffness and strength visualizations and minimizing weight, materials, and costs.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This powerful design tool has significantly improved both the standard of engineering designs and the design process methodology in many industrial applications.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] The introduction of FEM has substantially decreased the time to take products from concept to the production line.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Testing and development have been accelerated primarily through improved initial prototype designs using FEM.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In summary, benefits of FEM include increased accuracy, enhanced design and better insight into critical design parameters, virtual prototyping, fewer hardware prototypes, a faster and less expensive design cycle, increased productivity, and increased revenue.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] In the 1990s FEM was proposed for use in stochastic modeling for numerically solving probability models and later for reliability assessment.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] FEM is widely applied for approximating differential equations that describe physical systems.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] This method is very popular in the community of Computational fluid dynamics, and there are many applications for solving Navier–Stokes equations with FEM.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Recently, the application of FEM has been increasing in the researches of computational plasma.
[src:cloth-simulation/finite-element-method] Promising numerical results using FEM for Magnetohydrodynamics, Vlasov equation, and Schrödinger equation have been proposed.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In classical mechanics, a **harmonic oscillator** is a system that, when displaced from its equilibrium position, experiences a restoring force *F* proportional to the displacement *x*: ${\vec {F}}=-k{\vec {x}},$ where *k* is a positive constant.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The harmonic oscillator model is important in physics, because any mass subject to a force in stable equilibrium acts as a harmonic oscillator for small vibrations.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Harmonic oscillators occur widely in nature and are exploited in many manmade devices, such as clocks and radio circuits.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] If *F* is the only force acting on the system, the system is called a **simple harmonic oscillator**, and it undergoes simple harmonic motion: sinusoidal oscillations about the equilibrium point, with a constant amplitude and a constant frequency (which does not depend on the amplitude).
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] If a frictional force (damping) proportional to the velocity is also present, the harmonic oscillator is described as a **damped oscillator**.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The boundary solution between an underdamped oscillator and an overdamped oscillator occurs at a particular value of the friction coefficient and is called critically damped.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] If an external time-dependent force is present, the harmonic oscillator is described as a *driven oscillator*.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Mechanical examples include pendulums (with small angles of displacement), masses connected to springs, and acoustical systems.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Other analogous systems include electrical harmonic oscillators such as RLC circuits.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] They are the source of virtually all sinusoidal vibrations and waves.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] A simple harmonic oscillator is an oscillator that is neither driven nor damped.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] It consists of a mass m , which experiences a single force F , which pulls the mass in the direction of the point $x=0$ and depends only on the position x of the mass and a constant k .
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The motion is periodic, repeating itself in a sinusoidal fashion with constant amplitude *A*.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In addition to its amplitude, the motion of a simple harmonic oscillator is characterized by its period $T=2\pi /\omega$ , the time for a single oscillation or its frequency $f=1/T$ , the number of cycles per unit time.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The position at a given time *t* also depends on the phase $\varphi$ , which determines the starting point on the sine wave.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The period and frequency are determined by the size of the mass *m* and the force constant *k*, while the amplitude and phase are determined by the starting position and velocity.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The velocity and acceleration of a simple harmonic oscillator oscillate with the same frequency as the position, but with shifted phases.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The velocity is maximal for zero displacement, while the acceleration is in the direction opposite to the displacement.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In real oscillators, friction, or damping, slows the motion of the system.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Due to frictional force, the velocity decreases in proportion to the acting frictional force.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] While in a simple undriven harmonic oscillator the only force acting on the mass is the restoring force, in a damped harmonic oscillator there is in addition a frictional force which is always in a direction to oppose the motion.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In many vibrating systems the frictional force *F*f can be modeled as being proportional to the velocity *v* of the object: *F*f = −*cv*, where *c* is called the *viscous damping coefficient*.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The value of the damping ratio *ζ* critically determines the behavior of the system.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Driven harmonic oscillators (also called forced harmonic oscillators) are damped oscillators further affected by an externally applied force *F*(*t*).
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] and which can be expressed as damped sinusoidal oscillations: $z(t)=Ae^{-\zeta \omega _{0}t}\sin \left({\sqrt {1-\zeta ^{2}}}\omega _{0}t+\varphi \right),$ in the case where *ζ* ≤ 1.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The amplitude *A* and phase *φ* determine the behavior needed to match the initial conditions.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The time an oscillator needs to adapt to changed external conditions is of the order *τ* = 1/(*ζω*0).
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In physics, the adaptation is called relaxation, and *τ* is called the relaxation time.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In electrical engineering, a multiple of *τ* is called the *settling time*, i.e. the time necessary to ensure the signal is within a fixed departure from final value, typically within 10%.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The term *overshoot* refers to the extent the response maximum exceeds final value, and *undershoot* refers to the extent the response falls below final value for times following the response maximum.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] This type of system appears in AC-driven RLC circuits (resistor–inductor–capacitor) and driven spring systems having internal mechanical resistance or external air resistance.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] is the phase of the oscillation relative to the driving force.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The phase value is usually taken to be between −180° and 0 (that is, it represents a phase lag, for both positive and negative values of the arctan argument).
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] For a particular driving frequency called the resonance, or resonant frequency ${\textstyle \omega _{r}=\omega _{0}{\sqrt {1-2\zeta ^{2}}}}$ , the amplitude (for a given $F_{0}$ ) is maximal.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] This resonance effect only occurs when $\zeta <1/{\sqrt {2}}$ , i.e. for significantly underdamped systems.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] For strongly underdamped systems the value of the amplitude can become quite large near the resonant frequency.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The transient solutions are the same as the unforced ( $F_{0}=0$ ) damped harmonic oscillator and represent the system's response to other events that occurred previously.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] A parametric oscillator is a driven harmonic oscillator in which the drive energy is provided by varying the parameters of the oscillator, such as the damping or restoring force.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] A familiar example of parametric oscillation is "pumping" on a playground swing.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The varying of the parameters drives the system.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Examples of parameters that may be varied are its resonance frequency $\omega$ and damping $\beta$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric oscillators are used in many applications.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The classical varactor parametric oscillator oscillates when the diode's capacitance is varied periodically.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The circuit that varies the diode's capacitance is called the "pump" or "driver".
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In microwave electronics, waveguide/YAG based parametric oscillators operate in the same fashion.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The designer varies a parameter periodically to induce oscillations.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric oscillators have been developed as low-noise amplifiers, especially in the radio and microwave frequency range.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Thermal noise is minimal, since a reactance (not a resistance) is varied.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Another common use is frequency conversion, e.g., conversion from audio to radio frequencies.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] For example, the Optical parametric oscillator converts an input laser wave into two output waves of lower frequency ( $\omega _{s},\omega _{i}$ ).
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric resonance occurs in a mechanical system when a system is parametrically excited and oscillates at one of its resonant frequencies.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric excitation differs from forcing, since the action appears as a time varying modification on a system parameter.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] This effect is different from regular resonance because it exhibits the instability phenomenon.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The equation ${\frac {\mathrm {d} ^{2}q}{\mathrm {d} \tau ^{2}}}+2\zeta {\frac {\mathrm {d} q}{\mathrm {d} \tau }}+q=0$ is known as the **universal oscillator equation**, since all second-order linear oscillatory systems can be reduced to this form.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] This is done through nondimensionalization.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The solution to this differential equation contains two parts: the "transient" and the "steady-state".
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The transient solution is independent of the forcing function.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Compare this result with the theory section on resonance, as well as the "magnitude part" of the RLC circuit.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] This amplitude function is particularly important in the analysis and understanding of the frequency response of second-order systems.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] This phase function is particularly important in the analysis and understanding of the frequency response of second-order systems.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Harmonic oscillators occurring in a number of areas of engineering are equivalent in the sense that their mathematical models are identical (see universal oscillator equation above).
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Below is a table showing analogous quantities in four harmonic oscillator systems in mechanics and electronics.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] If analogous parameters on the same line in the table are given numerically equal values, the behavior of the oscillators – their output waveform, resonant frequency, damping factor, etc. – are the same.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The problem of the simple harmonic oscillator occurs frequently in physics, because a mass at equilibrium under the influence of any conservative force, in the limit of small motions, behaves as a simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] A conservative force is one that is associated with a potential energy.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Given an arbitrary potential-energy function $V(x)$ , one can do a Taylor expansion in terms of x around an energy minimum ( $x=x_{0}$ ) to model the behavior of small perturbations from equilibrium.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Thus, given an arbitrary potential-energy function $V(x)$ with a non-vanishing second derivative, one can use the solution to the simple harmonic oscillator to provide an approximate solution for small perturbations around the equilibrium point.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The general solution to this differential equation is $\theta (t)=A\cos \left({\sqrt {\frac {g}{l}}}t+\varphi \right),$ where A and $\varphi$ are constants that depend on the initial conditions.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Using as initial conditions $\theta (0)=\theta _{0}$ and ${\dot {\theta }}(0)=0$ , the solution is given by $\theta (t)=\theta _{0}\cos \left({\sqrt {\frac {g}{l}}}t\right),$ where $\theta _{0}$ is the largest angle attained by the pendulum (that is, $\theta _{0}$ is the amplitude of the pendulum).
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The period, the time for one complete oscillation, is given by the expression $\tau =2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {l}{g}}}={\frac {2\pi }{\omega }},$ which is a good approximation of the actual period when $\theta _{0}$ is small.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Notice that in this approximation the period $\tau$ is independent of the amplitude $\theta _{0}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In the above equation, $\omega$ represents the angular frequency.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] When a spring is stretched or compressed by a mass, the spring develops a restoring force.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Hooke's law gives the relationship of the force exerted by the spring when the spring is compressed or stretched a certain length: $F(t)=-kx(t),$ where *F* is the force, *k* is the spring constant, and *x* is the displacement of the mass with respect to the equilibrium position.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] The minus sign in the equation indicates that the force exerted by the spring always acts in a direction that is opposite to the displacement (i.e. the force always acts towards the zero position), and so prevents the mass from flying off to infinity.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] By using either force balance or an energy method, it can be readily shown that the motion of this system is given by the following differential equation: $F(t)=-kx(t)=m{\frac {\mathrm {d} ^{2}}{\mathrm {d} t^{2}}}x(t)=ma,$ the latter being Newton's second law of motion.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] Given an ideal massless spring, m is the mass on the end of the spring.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] If the spring itself has mass, its effective mass must be included in m .
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] In terms of energy, all systems have two types of energy: potential energy and kinetic energy.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] When a spring is stretched or compressed, it stores elastic potential energy, which is then transferred into kinetic energy.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] When the spring is stretched or compressed, kinetic energy of the mass gets converted into potential energy of the spring.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] By conservation of energy, assuming the datum is defined at the equilibrium position, when the spring reaches its maximal potential energy, the kinetic energy of the mass is zero.
[src:cloth-simulation/harmonic-oscillator] When the spring is released, it tries to return to equilibrium, and all its potential energy converts to kinetic energy of the mass.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The law is named after 17th-century British physicist Robert Hooke.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] He first stated the law in 1676 as a Latin anagram.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] He published the solution of his anagram in 1678 as: *ut tensio, sic vis* ("as the extension, so the force" or "the extension is proportional to the force").
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Hooke states in the 1678 work that he was aware of the law since 1660.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] It is the fundamental principle behind the spring scale, the manometer, the galvanometer, and the balance wheel of the mechanical clock.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The equation holds in many situations where an elastic body is deformed.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] An elastic body or material for which this equation can be assumed is said to be linear-elastic or **Hookean**.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law is a first-order linear approximation to the real response of springs and other elastic bodies to applied forces.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] It fails once the forces exceed some limit, since no material can be compressed beyond a certain minimum size, or stretched beyond a maximum size, without some permanent deformation or change of state.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Many materials will noticeably deviate from Hooke's law well before those elastic limits are reached.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The modern theory of elasticity generalizes Hooke's law to say that the strain (deformation) of an elastic object or material is proportional to the stress applied to it.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] However, since general stresses and strains may have multiple independent components, the "proportionality factor" may no longer be just a single real number, but rather a linear map (a tensor) that can be represented by a matrix of real numbers.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] In this general form, Hooke's law makes it possible to deduce the relation between strain and stress for complex objects in terms of intrinsic properties of the materials they are made of.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] For example, one can deduce that a homogeneous rod with uniform cross section will behave like a simple spring when stretched, with a stiffness k directly proportional to its cross-section area and inversely proportional to its length.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Consider a simple helical spring that has one end attached to some fixed object, while the free end is being pulled by a force whose magnitude is Fs.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Suppose that the spring has reached a state of equilibrium, where its length is not changing anymore.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Let x be the amount by which the free end of the spring was displaced from its "relaxed" position (when it is not being stretched).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law states that $F_{s}=kx$ or, equivalently, $x={\frac {F_{s}}{k}}$ where k is a positive real number, characteristic of the spring.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] A spring with spaces between the coils can be compressed, and the same formula holds for compression, with Fs and x both negative in that case.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] According to this formula, the graph of the applied force Fs as a function of the displacement x will be a straight line passing through the origin, whose slope is k.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law for a spring is also stated under the convention that Fs is the restoring force exerted by the spring on whatever is pulling its free end.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] In that case, the equation becomes $F_{s}=-kx$ since the direction of the restoring force is opposite to that of the displacement.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The torsional analog of Hooke's law applies to torsional springs.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] It states that the torque (τ) required to rotate an object is directly proportional to the angular displacement (θ) from the equilibrium position.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] It describes the relationship between the torque applied to an object and the resulting angular deformation due to torsion.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Just as in the linear case, this law shows that the torque is proportional to the angular displacement, and the negative sign indicates that the torque acts in a direction opposite to the angular displacement, providing a restoring force to bring the system back to equilibrium.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Hooke's spring law usually applies to any elastic object, of arbitrary complexity, as long as both the deformation and the stress can be expressed by a single number that can be both positive and negative.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] For example, when a block of rubber attached to two parallel plates is deformed by shearing, rather than stretching or compression, the shearing force *Fs* and the sideways displacement of the plates x obey Hooke's law (for small enough deformations).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law also applies when a straight steel bar or concrete beam (like the one used in buildings), supported at both ends, is bent by a weight F placed at some intermediate point.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The displacement x in this case is the deviation of the beam, measured in the transversal direction, relative to its unloaded shape.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] In the case of a helical spring that is stretched or compressed along its axis, the applied (or restoring) force and the resulting elongation or compression have the same direction (which is the direction of said axis).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Therefore, if Fs and x are defined as vectors, Hooke's equation still holds and says that the force vector is the elongation vector multiplied by a fixed scalar.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Some elastic bodies will deform in one direction when subjected to a force with a different direction.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] One example is a horizontal wood beam with non-square rectangular cross section that is bent by a transverse load that is neither vertical nor horizontal.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] In such cases, the *magnitude* of the displacement x will be proportional to the magnitude of the force Fs, as long as the direction of the latter remains the same (and its value is not too large); so the scalar version of Hooke's law *Fs* = −*kx* will hold.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] However, the force and displacement *vectors* will not be scalar multiples of each other, since they have different directions.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Moreover, the ratio k between their magnitudes will depend on the direction of the vector Fs.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Yet, in such cases there is often a fixed linear relation between the force and deformation vectors, as long as they are small enough.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Such a function is called a (second-order) tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] With respect to an arbitrary Cartesian coordinate system, the force and displacement vectors can be represented by 3 × 1 matrices of real numbers.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Therefore, Hooke's law **F** = ***κ*X** can be said to hold also when **X** and **F** are vectors with variable directions, except that the stiffness of the object is a tensor **κ**, rather than a single real number k.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The stresses and strains of the material inside a continuous elastic material (such as a block of rubber, the wall of a boiler, or a steel bar) are connected by a linear relationship that is mathematically similar to Hooke's spring law, and is often referred to by that name.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] However, the strain state in a solid medium around some point cannot be described by a single vector.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The same parcel of material, no matter how small, can be compressed, stretched, and sheared at the same time, along different directions.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Likewise, the stresses in that parcel can be at once pushing, pulling, and shearing.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] In order to capture this complexity, the relevant state of the medium around a point must be represented by two-second-order tensors, the strain tensor **ε** (in lieu of the displacement **X**) and the stress tensor **σ** (replacing the restoring force **F**).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The analogue of Hooke's spring law for continuous media is then ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}=\mathbf {c} {\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }},$ where **c** is a fourth-order tensor (that is, a linear map between second-order tensors) usually called the stiffness tensor or elasticity tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] One may also write it as ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}=\mathbf {s} {\boldsymbol {\sigma }},$ where the tensor **s**, called the compliance tensor, represents the inverse of said linear map.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Being a linear mapping between the nine numbers *σij* and the nine numbers *εkl*, the stiffness tensor **c** is represented by a matrix of 3 × 3 × 3 × 3 = 81 real numbers *cijkl*.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] All three tensors generally vary from point to point inside the medium, and may vary with time as well.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The strain tensor **ε** merely specifies the displacement of the medium particles in the neighborhood of the point, while the stress tensor **σ** specifies the forces that neighboring parcels of the medium are exerting on each other.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Therefore, they are independent of the composition and physical state of the material.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The stiffness tensor **c**, on the other hand, is a property of the material, and often depends on physical state variables such as temperature, pressure, and microstructure.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Due to the inherent symmetries of **σ**, **ε**, and **c**, only 21 elastic coefficients of the latter are independent.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] This number can be further reduced by the symmetry of the material: 9 for an orthorhombic crystal, 5 for an hexagonal structure, and 3 for a cubic symmetry.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] For isotropic media (which have the same physical properties in any direction), **c** can be reduced to only two independent numbers, the bulk modulus K and the shear modulus G, that quantify the material's resistance to changes in volume and to shearing deformations, respectively.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Since Hooke's law is a simple proportionality between two quantities, its formulas and consequences are mathematically similar to those of many other physical laws, such as those describing the motion of fluids, or the polarization of a dielectric by an electric field.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] In SI units, displacements are measured in meters (m), and forces in newtons (N or kg·m/s2).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Therefore, the spring constant k, and each element of the tensor **κ**, is measured in newtons per meter (N/m), or kilograms per second squared (kg/s2).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] For continuous media, each element of the stress tensor **σ** is a force divided by an area; it is therefore measured in units of pressure, namely pascals (Pa, or N/m2, or kg/(m·s2).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The elements of the strain tensor **ε** are dimensionless (displacements divided by distances).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Therefore, the entries of cijkl are also expressed in units of pressure.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Objects that quickly regain their original shape after being deformed by a force, with the molecules or atoms of their material returning to the initial state of stable equilibrium, often obey Hooke's law.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law only holds for some materials under certain loading conditions.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Steel exhibits linear-elastic behavior in most engineering applications; Hooke's law is valid for it throughout its **elastic range** (i.e., for stresses below the yield strength).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] For some other materials, such as aluminium, Hooke's law is only valid for a portion of the elastic range.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] For these materials a proportional limit stress is defined, below which the errors associated with the linear approximation are negligible.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Rubber is generally regarded as a "non-Hookean" material because its elasticity is stress dependent and sensitive to temperature and loading rate.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Generalizations of Hooke's law for the case of large deformations is provided by models of neo-Hookean solids and Mooney–Rivlin solids.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] A rod of any elastic material may be viewed as a linear spring.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The rod has length L and cross-sectional area A.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The modulus of elasticity may often be considered constant.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The potential energy *U*el(*x*) stored in a spring is given by $U_{\mathrm {el} }(x)={\tfrac {1}{2}}kx^{2}$ which comes from adding up the energy it takes to incrementally compress the spring.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] That is, the integral of force over displacement.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Since the external force has the same general direction as the displacement, the potential energy of a spring is always non-negative.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] This potential *U*el can be visualized as a parabola on the Ux-plane such that *U*el(*x*) = ⁠1/2⁠*kx*2.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] As the spring is stretched in the positive x-direction, the potential energy increases parabolically (the same thing happens as the spring is compressed).
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Since the change in potential energy changes at a constant rate: ${\frac {d^{2}U_{\mathrm {el} }}{dx^{2}}}=k\,.$ Note that the change in the change in U is constant even when the displacement and acceleration are zero.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Just as the potential energy can be written as a quadratic form in the internal coordinates, so it can also be written in terms of generalized forces.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The resulting coefficients are termed compliance constants.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] A direct method exists for calculating the compliance constant for any internal coordinate of a molecule, without the need to do the normal mode analysis.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The suitability of relaxed force constants (inverse compliance constants) as covalent bond strength descriptors was demonstrated as early as 1980.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Recently, the suitability as non-covalent bond strength descriptors was demonstrated too.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] A mass m attached to the end of a spring is a classic example of a harmonic oscillator.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] By pulling slightly on the mass and then releasing it, the system will be set in sinusoidal oscillating motion about the equilibrium position.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Isotropic materials are characterized by properties which are independent of direction in space.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Physical equations involving isotropic materials must therefore be independent of the coordinate system chosen to represent them.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The strain tensor is a symmetric tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Since the trace of any tensor is independent of any coordinate system, the most complete coordinate-free decomposition of a symmetric tensor is to represent it as the sum of a constant tensor and a traceless symmetric tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] where **I** is the second-order identity tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The first term on the right is the constant tensor, also known as the **volumetric strain tensor**, and the second term is the traceless symmetric tensor, also known as the **deviatoric strain tensor** or shear tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Using the relationships between the elastic moduli, these equations may also be expressed in various other ways.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] This is the form in which the strain is expressed in terms of the stress tensor in engineering.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The three-dimensional form of Hooke's law can be derived using Poisson's ratio and the one-dimensional form of Hooke's law as follows.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Similar treatment of directions 2 and 3 gives the Hooke's law in three dimensions.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The symmetry of the Cauchy stress tensor (*σij* = *σji*) and the generalized Hooke's laws (*σij* = *cijklεkl*) implies that *cijkl* = *cjikl*.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Similarly, the symmetry of the infinitesimal strain tensor implies that *cijkl* = *cijlk*.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] These symmetries are called the **minor symmetries** of the stiffness tensor **c**.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] This reduces the number of elastic constants from 81 to 36.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] These are called the **major symmetries** of the stiffness tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] This reduces the number of elastic constants from 36 to 21.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The major and minor symmetries indicate that the stiffness tensor has only 21 independent components.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] It is often useful to express the anisotropic form of Hooke's law in matrix notation, also called Voigt notation.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] $c_{pqrs}=l_{pi}l_{qj}l_{rk}l_{sl}c_{ijkl}$ where lab are the components of an orthogonal rotation matrix [*L*].
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The same relation also holds for inversions.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Orthotropic materials have three orthogonal planes of symmetry.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] A transversely isotropic material is symmetric with respect to a rotation about an axis of symmetry.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] To grasp the degree of anisotropy of any class, a **universal elastic anisotropy index** (AU) was formulated.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] It replaces the Zener ratio, which is suited for cubic crystals.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Linear deformations of elastic materials can be approximated as adiabatic.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] Under these conditions and for quasistatic processes the first law of thermodynamics for a deformed body can be expressed as $\delta W=\delta U$ where δU is the increase in internal energy and δW is the work done by external forces.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The work can be split into two terms $\delta W=\delta W_{\mathrm {s} }+\delta W_{\mathrm {b} }$ where *δW*s is the work done by surface forces while *δW*b is the work done by body forces.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] The right-hand side constant requires four indices and is a fourth-rank quantity.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] We can also see that this quantity must be a tensor because it is a linear transformation that takes the strain tensor to the stress tensor.
[src:cloth-simulation/hooke-s-law] We can also show that the constant obeys the tensor transformation rules for fourth-rank tensors.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:cloth-simulation/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The simulation of volumetric solid soft bodies can be realised by using a variety of approaches.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] In this approach, the body is modeled as a set of point masses (nodes) connected by ideal weightless elastic springs obeying some variant of Hooke's law.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Additional springs between nodes can be added, or the force law of the springs modified, to achieve desired effects.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Rendering of a three-dimensional mass-spring lattice is often done using free-form deformation, in which the rendered mesh is embedded in the lattice and distorted to conform to the shape of the lattice as it evolves.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Assuming all point masses equal to zero one can obtain the Stretched grid method aimed at several engineering problems solution relative to the elastic grid behavior.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] These are sometimes known as mass-spring-damper models.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] In pressurized soft bodies spring-mass model is combined with a pressure force based on the ideal gas law.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] This is a more physically accurate approach, which uses the widely used finite element method to solve the partial differential equations which govern the dynamics of an elastic material.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The body is modeled as a three-dimensional elastic continuum by breaking it into a large number of solid elements which fit together, and solving for the stresses and strains in each element using a model of the material.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The elements are typically tetrahedral, the nodes being the vertices of the tetrahedra (relatively simple methods exist to *tetrahedralize* a three dimensional region bounded by a polygon mesh into tetrahedra, similarly to how a two-dimensional polygon may be *triangulated* into triangles).
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The strain (which measures the local deformation of the points of the material from their rest state) is quantified by the strain tensor ${\boldsymbol {\epsilon }}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The stress (which measures the local forces per-unit area in all directions acting on the material) is quantified by the Cauchy stress tensor ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}$ .
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The equation of motion of the element nodes is obtained by integrating the stress field over each element and relating this, via Newton's second law, to the node accelerations.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Pixelux (developers of the Digital Molecular Matter system) use a finite-element-based approach for their soft bodies, using a tetrahedral mesh and converting the stress tensor directly into node forces.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Rendering is done via a form of free-form deformation.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] This approach is motivated by variational principles and the physics of surfaces, which dictate that a constrained surface will assume the shape which minimizes the total energy of deformation (analogous to a soap bubble).
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] In this scheme, penalty forces or constraints are applied to the model to drive it towards its original shape (i.e. the material behaves as if it has shape memory).
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] To conserve momentum the rotation of the body must be estimated properly, for example via polar decomposition.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] To approximate finite element simulation, shape matching can be applied to three dimensional lattices and multiple shape matching constraints blended.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Deformation can also be handled by a traditional rigid-body physics engine, modeling the soft-body motion using a network of multiple rigid bodies connected by constraints, and using (for example) matrix-palette skinning to generate a surface mesh for rendering.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] This is the approach used for deformable objects in Havok Destruction.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Via rendering effects, this can produce a visually plausible emulation of textiles and clothing, used in a variety of contexts in video games, animation, and film.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] It can also be used to simulate two dimensional sheets of materials other than textiles, such as deformable metal panels or vegetation.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] In video games it is often used to enhance the realism of clothed animated characters.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Cloth simulators are generally based on mass-spring models, but a distinction must be made between force-based and position-based solvers.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The mass-spring model (obtained from a polygonal mesh representation of the cloth) determines the internal spring forces acting on the nodes at each timestep (in combination with gravity and applied forces).
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Newton's second law gives equations of motion which can be solved via standard ODE solvers.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Therefore, implicit solvers must be used, requiring solution of a large sparse matrix system (via e.g. the conjugate gradient method), which itself may also be difficult to achieve at interactive frame rates.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] An alternative is to use an explicit method with low stiffness, with *ad hoc* methods to avoid instability and excessive stretching (e.g. strain limiting corrections).
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] To avoid needing to do an expensive implicit solution of a system of ODEs, many real-time cloth simulators (notably PhysX, Havok Cloth, and Maya nCloth) use *position based dynamics* (PBD), an approach based on constraint relaxation.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The mass-spring model is converted into a system of constraints, which demands that the distance between the connected nodes be equal to the initial distance.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] This system is solved sequentially and iteratively, by directly moving nodes to satisfy each constraint, until sufficiently stiff cloth is obtained.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] This is similar to a Gauss-Seidel solution of the implicit matrix system for the mass-spring model.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Care must be taken though to solve the constraints in the same sequence each timestep, to avoid spurious oscillations, and to make sure that the constraints do not violate linear and angular momentum conservation.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Additional position constraints can be applied, for example to keep the nodes within desired regions of space (sufficiently close to an animated model for example), or to maintain the body's overall shape via shape matching.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Realistic interaction of simulated soft objects with their environment may be important for obtaining visually realistic results.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Cloth self-intersection is important in some applications for acceptably realistic simulated garments.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] This is challenging to achieve at interactive frame rates, particularly in the case of detecting and resolving self collisions and mutual collisions between two or more deformable objects.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Collision detection may be *discrete/a posteriori* (meaning objects are advanced in time through a pre-determined interval, and then any penetrations detected and resolved), or *continuous/a priori* (objects are advanced only until a collision occurs, and the collision is handled before proceeding).
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] The former is easier to implement and faster, but leads to failure to detect collisions (or detection of spurious collisions) if objects move fast enough.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Real-time systems generally have to use discrete collision detection, with other *ad hoc* ways to avoid failing to detect collisions.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Detection of collisions between cloth and environmental objects with a well defined "inside" is straightforward since the system can detect unambiguously whether the cloth mesh vertices and faces are intersecting the body and resolve them accordingly.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] If a well defined "inside" does not exist (e.g. in the case of collision with a mesh which does not form a closed boundary), an "inside" may be constructed via extrusion.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Mutual- or self-collisions of soft bodies defined by tetrahedra is straightforward, since it reduces to detection of collisions between solid tetrahedra.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] However, detection of collisions between two polygonal cloths (or collision of a cloth with itself) via discrete collision detection is much more difficult, since there is no unambiguous way to locally detect after a timestep whether a cloth node which has penetrated is on the "wrong" side or not.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Solutions involve either using the history of the cloth motion to determine if an intersection event has occurred, or doing a global analysis of the cloth state to detect and resolve self-intersections.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Pixar has presented a method which uses a global topological analysis of mesh intersections in configuration space to detect and resolve self-interpenetration of cloth.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Currently, this is generally too computationally expensive for real-time cloth systems.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] To do collision detection efficiently, primitives which are certainly not colliding must be identified as soon as possible and discarded from consideration to avoid wasting time.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] To do this, some form of spatial subdivision scheme is essential, to avoid a brute force test of $O[n^{2}]$ primitive collisions.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] Simulating fluids in the context of computer graphics would not normally be considered soft-body dynamics, which is usually restricted to mean simulation of materials which have a tendency to retain their shape and form.
[src:cloth-simulation/soft-body-dynamics] In contrast, a fluid assumes the shape of whatever vessel contains it, as the particles are bound together by relatively weak forces.
